# learning ai integration vs ai eval — both are right, at different layers


# the take

# both takes are right, and they're not actually in conflict — they're at
# different layers of the same stack.


# the "learn integration, not a tool" advice

# correct, but slightly under-specified. the real skill it's pointing at is:
#
#     treat the llm as a component, not as the system.
#
# that mental shift is the actual unlock. once you stop thinking "i'm using
# ai" and start thinking "i have a stochastic function in my pipeline that
# takes json and returns json," everything else falls into place. you start
# asking normal engineering questions: what's the input contract, what's the
# output contract, what's the failure mode, how do i retry, how do i cache,
# how do i observe it, how do i swap implementations.


# why "learn the api, not a framework" is right

# - api surfaces (openai, anthropic, gemini, openrouter, bedrock) are 90% the
#   same — messages: [{role, content}], tools, streaming. learn one, you've
#   learned them all.
# - cli tools and frameworks (langchain, llamaindex, vercel ai sdk, mastra,
#   dspy, etc.) come and go. some will be dead in 18 months. the underlying
#   api will not.
# - "glue" is where the value gets created. raw model output is worthless
#   until it's hooked to a database, a queue, a tool, a ui, a downstream
#   service.


# where to push back gently

# "integration" alone is necessary but not sufficient. you can be a beautiful
# integrator and ship a beautiful pipeline that produces consistently wrong
# output, and you won't know. that's why eval is the load-bearing skill — but
# integration is the foundation underneath eval.


# the relationship

# integration  →  you can build it                  (engineering)
# eval         →  you can tell if it's working      (epistemics)
# agents       →  you can let it run unsupervised   (systems)
#
# you need integration first, because eval and agents both *assume* you can
# wire model calls into a system. but once you can wire them, the next
# bottleneck is "is this output actually good?" — and that's eval.


# revised take

# if you've never written code that calls an llm api: learn integration first.
# spend a weekend wiring anthropic.messages.create() or
# openai.chat.completions.create() into something real — a script, a webhook,
# a small tool. don't use a framework. make the json calls directly.
# understand:
#
# - the message shape, system vs user vs assistant turns
# - streaming vs non-streaming
# - tool use (function calling) — where 80% of the value comes from
# - structured output (json mode / response_format)
# - token counting, context windows, cost per million tokens
# - error handling and retry on rate limits
# - prompt caching (anthropic) / context caching (gemini) — the cost lever
#   almost nobody uses
#
# that's a weekend's work and it's the foundation everything else sits on.
# you can ignore every framework on the market once you've done this — they
# are all just thin sugar over those same api calls.
#
# then, once you can build pipelines: learn eval. because now the question
# stops being "can i build this?" and starts being "is what i built actually
# good?" — and that's where most teams plateau.


# the combined one-liner

# learn to treat the llm as a function in your system, wire it in by hand
# against the raw api, and build feedback loops that tell you whether the
# function is doing what you think it's doing.
#
# integration is how you build with ai.
# eval is whether what you built works.
# you need both. the order is integration → eval → agents.


# practical advice

# if you're picking one weekend project to internalize all of this, build an
# eval harness for your own integration. that gets you both skills at once:
# - you call the api directly (integration)
# - you wire it into a scoring loop (eval)
# - you learn the entire stack from one project
# there's no faster path.
#
# see also: [[ai-eval-skill]]
